desc: Based on its size economic profile (mid‐sized city with modest industry and services) and comparison to the provided benchmarks Nowy Sącz (Małopolskie) would fall into the Medium class.

Based on Kwaczała’s location in Chrzanowski county (an industrial–commuter district on the outskirts of the Kraków metro area) and benchmarking it against similar Polish districts its regional GDP class is best rated as: Medium.

Based on its location in a relatively rural part of Lubliniecki county (Śląskie Voivodeship) outside the main industrial/urban core of the region Koszęcin’s district-level GDP would fall into the Low category.  
Answer: Low

Based on its location in Rudziniec (Gliwice County) in the heart of the Upper Silesian industrial‐metropolitan area – with strong spill-over from Gliwice/Katowice well-developed infrastructure and higher‐than‐average per-capita output – Ligota Łabędzka’s district would be classed as Very High.

Based on Kobiór’s location in Pszczyński county (part of the very strong Upper Silesian economic core) you’d place its district‐level GDP into the top bracket.  
Answer: Very High
Based on Popowice’s location within Wrocław—a top‐tier economic hub in Poland with one of the highest regional GDPs in the country—its district‐level GDP falls into the “Very High” class.

Based on the economic profile of Tuchola County – a predominantly rural forestry‐and‐agriculture district with no large urban or industrial centre and no significant tourism base – its per-district GDP is well below the national and voivodeship averages. By comparison with the provided benchmarks (where rural Lubelskie or Mazowieckie localities scored “Low” and only exceptionally remote or mountainous areas dropped to “Very Low”) Tucholski (Kujawsko-pomorskie) best fits the “Low” class. 

Answer: Low

Based on its location in the generally under-performing Warmińsko-Mazurskie voivodeship and the fact that Ramsowo lies in the rural Olsztyński powiat (excluding the higher-output city of Olsztyn itself) its district’s GDP cluster falls into the “Low” category.
Based on its location in a small rural part of Giżycko County in the generally lower‐GDP Warmian-Masurian Voivodeship Radzie falls into the “Low” category.

Based on its location in a predominantly rural part of Sieradz County (Łódzkie voivodeship) – which sits below the national‐average GDP per capita but above the poorest eastern provinces – Wola Będkowska would be classified as Medium.

Based on its location in a rural part of eastern Poland (Lubelskie province) similar to other Lubelskie‐area villages (e.g. Czołki) which were classified as “Low” Polubicze Wiejskie would likewise fall into the Low class.
Based on Mielecki’s position – a mid‐sized industrial district in relatively low-GDP Podkarpackie (despite its SEZ and aviation cluster) – it would fall into the Medium class.

Based on its location in the highly productive capital‐region economy of Warsaw (Mazowieckie being by far Poland’s top NUTS 2 in GDP per capita) and the urban service‐and‐finance character of Praga-Południe this district falls into the Very High class.  
Answer: Very High

Based on its location in a largely rural outlying part of Ciechanów County (Glinojeck gmina) – outside the Warsaw commuter belt and without any major industrial or service centre – its likely district‐level GDP falls into the “Low” class.

Based on its being a rural county (powiat) surrounding – but not including – the city of Płock (which is a separate city‐county) and by analogy to similarly structured counties like Siedlecki or Zamojski Płocki’s district GDP falls into the “Low” class.
Bratislavský kraj is by far the richest Slovak region (roughly €40–50 billion GDP) placing it firmly in the “Very High” category.

Based on the fact that Dolný Kubín lies in the Žilina Region – whose GDP is on the order of €8–10 billion per year roughly in line with Hungary’s Szabolcs-Szatmár-Bereg (assigned “Medium”) – we would likewise classify Žilinský kraj as Medium.

Based on Mýtna’s location in the Lučenec district of the Banská Bystrica (Banskobystrický) Region – one of Slovakia’s lower‐GDP regions outside the Bratislava core – the appropriate class is:

Answer: Low

Based on its position among Slovakia’s eight kraje – Košický kraj generates roughly €7–8 billion putting it squarely in the middle of the pack (behind Bratislava Trnava Trenčín and Žilina but ahead of Nitra Prešov and Banská Bystrica) – we would classify Južné Mesto (Košice IV Košice region) as Medium.

Based on the fact that Lukov (418 04) lies in the Teplice okres of Ústecký kraj – a mid‐sized industrial NUTS 3 unit whose total annual output is neither among the very smallest nor the very largest in our CZ/HU/PL/SK comparison – its GDP class falls into the middle tier.  

Answer: Medium

Based on its placement in the Czech regional hierarchy and by comparison with the Pardubický kraj (previously rated “Very High”) the Olomoucký kraj also falls into the top category.  

Answer: Very High

Based on Komárom‐Esztergom’s position in the relatively well-performing Central Transdanubia region of Hungary (with above-national‐average per-capita output strong industry around Tatabánya and Komárom etc.) the county-level GDP class for Tata (post code 2890) would be judged as High.

Based on Söjtör’s location in rural Zala County—which sits below Hungary’s national average GDP with limited industry beyond agriculture and small‐scale services—the most appropriate classification is:

Answer: Low
Based on its location in Borsod-Abaúj-Zemplén – one of Hungary’s lowest‐output counties (and in the country’s poorest NUTS‐2 region) – Szikszó’s per‐capita GDP would fall into the Very Low class.

Based on its being in Hajdú-Bihar (an Eastern Hungarian county with a GDP per capita in the mid‐range of regional benchmarks similar to Szabolcs-Szatmár-Bereg which was judged “Medium”) I’d classify Ebes’s regional GDP as Medium.
